{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-91f6dea56f3c58cc", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tAuditing Protocol-Level Shortcuts in Large Audio\n2\tLanguage Model Judges for Speech Evaluation\n3\tJoonyong Park† , David M. Chan‡ , Yuki Saito† , Hiroshi Saruwatari†\n4\t† Graduate School of Information Science and Technology, The University of Tokyo, Tokyo, Japan\n5\t‡ Berkeley AI Research (BAIR), University of California, Berkeley, CA, USA\n6\t\n7\tarXiv:2607.13477v1 [cs.SD] 15 Jul 2026\n8\t\n9\tjoonyong-park@g.ecc.u-tokyo.ac.jp\n10\t\n11\tAbstract—Large audio-language models (LALMs) are increasingly used as automatic judges for speech evaluation. However,\n12\thigh agreement with human ratings does not guarantee that their\n13\tverdicts are grounded in the audio. A judge may instead rely\n14\ton specialist labels or reference data supplied by the evaluation\n15\tprotocol itself, taking a shortcut in place of listening to the\n16\taudio. In this paper, we audit such protocol-level “shortcuts”\n17\tin LALM judges across three common deployment protocols:\n18\tfeature-blueprint judging, where the audio is replaced by a structured text description of acoustic features, reference-conditioned\n19\tjudging, and pairwise A/B comparison. Across six judges and\n20\tfour attributes, we find that several LALMs rely on protocol-level\n21\tshortcuts. For example, in feature-blueprint judging, incorrect\n22\tspecialist labels reduce five judges’ emotion accuracy to 0.10\n23\tor below, and in concatenated A/B comparisons, Qwen3-OmniThinking often picks the same slot regardless of order swaps.\n24\tThese results indicate that aggregate agreement can overstate\n25\tthe validity of LALM judges unless the model and the evaluation\n26\tprotocol are assessed jointly, and that each model-protocol pair\n27\tshould be evaluated with a matched shortcut probe.\n28\tIndex Terms—LALMs, LALM-as-judge, evaluation protocols,\n29\tpairwise judging.\n30\t\n31\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n32\tLarge audio-language models (LALMs) process spoken\n33\taudio, non-speech sound, music, and text instructions within\n34\tone interface [1]–[5], and can reach human-comparable accuracy on many audio understanding tasks. This capability has\n35\tmotivated their use as automatic judges for speech evaluation,\n36\ti.e., LALM-as-a-judge, following the broader LLM-as-a-judge\n37\tparadigm [6]–[8]. In this paradigm, an LALM can serve as\n38\ta proxy for human raters on mean opinion score (MOS)\n39\tprediction, A/B preference, style-instruction following, and\n40\tparalinguistic assessment [9]–[12].\n41\tResearchers typically validate these judges using aggregate agreement with human labels. However, this validation\n42\tcan overlook agreement induced by the evaluation protocol.\n43\tAlthough the side information supplied by each protocol is\n44\tmeant to help with evaluation, we observe that this information\n45\tcan function as a label-informative side channel that leads\n46\tto shortcuts. Examples include reference following, positional\n47\tbiases in pairwise audio judging [13], and specialist-field\n48\tshortcuts in feature-mediated judging [14].\n49\tSuch non-audio reliance is already documented outside\n50\tLALMs as a judge. For example, in understanding tasks,\n51\tseveral LALMs retain their audio accuracy when the audio is\n52\tremoved or contradicts the text, relying on transcript semantics\n53\tor language priors [15]–[18]. Within judging itself, prior audits\n54\t\n55\texamine one channel at a time—position bias in a single\n56\tpairwise recipe [13], or modality stability in a single pointwise\n57\tsetup [19]. None asks, however, across the protocols used to\n58\tdeploy these judges, which shortcut each one opens.\n59\tIn this paper we investigate LALM-as-a-judge at the protocol level, treating each judge as a measurement protocol,\n60\texamining whether the side information it supplies is used as\n61\tevidence or as a shortcut. We study three evaluation protocols\n62\t(Fig. 1), leading to three overall research questions:\n63\t• RQ1 (feature-blueprint): given a text description of\n64\tacoustic features that includes a label predicted by a\n65\tseparate specialist classifier, does the judge reason over\n66\tthe features, or copy that classifier’s label?\n67\t• RQ2 (reference-conditioned): given a reference label\n68\talongside the target clip, does the judge use it to inform\n69\tits own audio judgment or does the verdict shift toward\n70\tthe reference, even when the reference is wrong?\n71\t• RQ3 (pairwise): given two clips to compare, does the\n72\tverdict follow which clip sounds better, or which one is\n73\tpresented first?\n74\tIn each evaluation, we pair a protocol with a matching countercondition that should not change a valid audio-based verdict,\n75\tand evaluate the output of the judges across four attributes:\n76\temotion, naturalness, language, and speaker similarity probes.\n77\tOverall, we find both the reference-anchor and pairwiseposition shortcuts appear across multiple attributes, suggesting\n78\tthat they are protocol-level effects. Wrong reference labels\n79\tare followed at similar prompt positions for both emotion and\n80\tlanguage judgments, and A/B position bias appears in both\n81\tnaturalness and speaker-similarity comparisons. Furthermore,\n82\tjudges often copy a wrong emotion label even when audio is\n83\tpresent, while they reject a wrong language label as they can\n84\tinfer language directly from the audio.\n85\tWe make three contributions: (i) a protocol-level reframing\n86\tof LALM-as-a-judge that maps each deployment protocol to\n87\ta characteristic shortcut, (ii) a matched diagnostic for each\n88\tprotocol that identifies which judges are usable under it,\n89\tand (iii) a cross-attribute analysis separating protocol-level\n90\tshortcuts from a capability-dependent one.\n91\tII. R ELATED W ORK\n92\tA. LLM-as-judge: position, reference, and audio reliance\n93\tIn the LLM-as-judge paradigm, a strong model scores or\n94\tcompares candidate outputs in place of human raters, provid-\n95\t\n96\t\fRQ1: Feature-Blueprint\n97\t\n98\tRQ2: Reference-Conditioned\n99\t\n100\tRQ3: Pairwise A/B\n101\t\n102\tDoes audio override a wrong label?\n103\t\n104\tHow often does the judge output wrong references?\n105\t\n106\tWill judge choose same slot or same audio?\n107\tFormat Control\n108\t\n109\tOrder Swap\n110\t\n111\t“You’re given a structured description of a spoken utterance:\n112\tDescription: {blueprint}\n113\t\n114\tbeep\n115\t\n116\tAB:\n117\t\n118\tconcat:\n119\t\n120\tBA:\n121\t\n122\tnative:\n123\t\n124\t|\n125\t\n126\t① before: the reference label is (wrong-label)\n127\ttranscript\n128\t\n129\tmetadata\n130\t\n131\tacoustic descriptors\n132\t\n133\taffect label: (e.g.)\n134\t• ‘happy’ ‘english’ (true-label)\n135\t• ‘sad’ ‘french’ (wrong-label)\n136\t\n137\tIdentify the speaker’s (emotion/language).\n138\t\n139\tWhich clip sounds more\n140\t(cleaner/emotive/natural/*same-speaker) ?\n141\tReply with A or B.\n142\t\n143\t② after: the reference label is (wrong-label)\n144\t③ system: [INSTRUCTIONS: the reference label is (wrong-label)]\n145\t\n146\tIdentify the speaker’s (emotion / language).\n147\t\n148\t④ rubric: Hint: a classifier has labeled this clip as (wrong-label)\n149\t\n150\tEvaluation: wrong-label + audio accuracy\n151\t\n152\tEvaluation: reference-follow rate (output = wrong ref.)\n153\t\n154\t*speaker:\n155\t(triplet)\n156\t\n157\tGiven reference, does speaker same or different?\n158\t\n159\tEvaluation: lock (same-slot rate) and accuracy\n160\t\n161\tFig. 1. Overview of protocol-level shortcut audits for LALM judges: feature-blueprint copying, reference-label following, and pairwise slot or format bias.\n162\t\n163\ting a scalable and reproducible proxy for human evaluation.\n164\tIt was introduced for text evaluation by MT-Bench [6] and\n165\textended to multimodal settings such as caption evaluation\n166\tby CLAIR and CLAIR-A [7], [8]. More recently, the same\n167\tframework has been applied to speech, where LALMs serve as\n168\tjudges for MOS prediction, A/B preference, and paralinguistic\n169\tassessment [9], [10], [12].\n170\tHowever, a recurring concern is that the verdict tracks\n171\tfeatures of the prompt rather than answer quality. Position\n172\tbias is the most studied failure mode in text LLM judges,\n173\twhere swapping the order of two candidates can flip the\n174\tranking [20]. For audio judges, AudioJudge [13] further shows\n175\tthat audio-LLMs trained on single-audio inputs default to positional heuristics when two clips are concatenated. Although\n176\tit characterizes the concatenation recipe, it does not address\n177\thow the bias behaves across judges, as the quality gap widens,\n178\tor under native multi-audio input.\n179\tBeyond position, supplied side information can affect text\n180\tLLM judges’ verdicts. They exhibit authority bias by following an authoritative or fabricated reference even when it is\n181\twrong [21]. They also show sycophancy, by conforming to a\n182\tprovided answer or rebuttal [22], [23]. These reference effects\n183\tare documented for text candidates and are neither localized to\n184\ta prompt position nor measured when the evidence is audio.\n185\tIn parallel, work on audio reliance shows that several\n186\tLALMs retain much of their full-audio score when the audio is\n187\tremoved [15]. They also follow lexical over acoustic cues under controlled conflicts [16], [17], and select language-implied\n188\tanswers in paralinguistic tasks [18]. However, these studies\n189\tmeasure models answering questions, not judges operating\n190\tthrough protocols that supply side information.\n191\tThis tendency is an instance of shortcut learning, in which\n192\tmodels can prefer the simplest cue sufficient for the answer [24], [25]. At inference time, they may follow shortcuts in\n193\tthe prompt rather than information in the weights [26]. However, whether such prompt shortcuts depend on the model’s\n194\tcapability has not been examined for audio judges.\n195\tB. Feature-mediated judging and specialist label copying\n196\tFeature-mediated judging converts speech into structured\n197\tacoustic descriptions for a text LLM. TRACE constructs\n198\ttextual “blueprints” of audio cues for LLM judges [14], which\n199\tcover content, voice quality, and paralinguistics. This format\n200\t\n201\tmakes the evidence explicit and reduces dependence on the\n202\tperceptual component of audio-language models.\n203\tA blueprint, however, can contain target-proximal fields\n204\tproduced by specialist classifiers that predict the same label the\n205\tjudge must output. In this case, a reported gain may reflect the\n206\tjudge reproducing the specialist’s label rather than reasoning\n207\tover the lower-level acoustic descriptors. Existing featuremediated evaluations report the score without separating these\n208\ttwo sources, and without examining when the copy occurs.\n209\tIII. M ETHOD\n210\tA trustworthy judge should treat the audio as the ground\n211\ttruth and the protocol’s side information as, at most, a hint:\n212\twhen the two agree, accuracy should stay high, and when the\n213\tside information is deliberately wrong, a good judge should\n214\tignore it and remain audio-grounded rather than follow it.\n215\tPrior audits, however, leave two gaps: they probe a single\n216\tprotocol at a fixed prompt position, and they do not separate\n217\ta copied specialist label from genuine acoustic reasoning. To\n218\taddress these gaps, we treat each judge as a measurement\n219\tprotocol: a procedure that, to be trustworthy, must return a\n220\tverdict that is stable under irrelevant changes and grounded in\n221\tthe audio. We audit three deployment protocols and pair each\n222\twith a matched counter-condition that should leave a valid\n223\taudio-based verdict unchanged. If a judge instead tracks the\n224\tside information under this condition, the counter-condition\n225\texposes a shortcut. We define each protocol over a target\n226\tattribute, a property of the clip the judge must evaluate, and\n227\trun it on more than one attribute. By doing so, we can tell\n228\twhether a shortcut is tied to a particular task or is a property\n229\tof the protocol itself.\n230\tA. Notation and metrics\n231\tA judge M maps an input to a prediction ŷM (x) for clip\n232\tx, which we compare against the ground-truth attribute value\n233\ty(x). Each experiment contrasts the audio-grounded verdict\n234\twith a counter-condition that adds or alters a text channel; the\n235\tconditions are named where they are used (§III-B–§III-D).\n236\tFor a clip set C and a categorical attribute, predictions are\n237\tscored by top-1 accuracy against y(x). For naturalness, which\n238\tis continuous, the pairwise protocol treats the higher-MOS clip\n239\tas the gold choice. Also, a judge’s output is unparseable when\n240\tno valid label can be extracted from it (e.g. an empty response,\n241\ta refusal, or free text that names none of the K classes), which\n242\t\n243\t\fTABLE I\n244\tATTRIBUTES , CORPORA , SPECIALIST, AND ITS TOP -1 ACCURACY ON THAT\n245\tATTRIBUTE ’ S PROBE SET AGAINST GROUND - TRUTH LABELS . ‘G OLD ’\n246\tINDICATES THAT THE CORPUS IS LABELED BY HUMANS , SO NO\n247\tACCURACY IS REPORTED .\n248\t\n249\tAlso, since the chance level of RF is 1/(K−1) for a Kclass attribute, we report the chance-normalized referencefollow rate:\n250\t\u0011\n251\t\u0010\n252\tf\n253\t(2)\n254\tRF(M\n255\t) = max 0, RF(M )−(1/(K−1)) .\n256\t1−(1/(K−1))\n257\t\n258\tAttribute\n259\t\n260\tCorpus\n261\t\n262\tSpecialist\n263\t\n264\tEmotion\n265\tRAVDESS emotion2vec+\n266\tLanguage\n267\tFLEURS\n268\twhisper-LID\n269\tNaturalness BVCC\n270\thuman MOS\n271\tSpeaker\n272\tVoxCeleb1 ECAPA-TDNN\n273\t\n274\tAccuracy\n275\t\n276\tProtocols\n277\t\n278\t0.80\n279\t1.00\n280\tGold\n281\t1.00\n282\t\n283\tRQ1, RQ2, RQ3\n284\tRQ1, RQ2\n285\tRQ3\n286\tRQ3\n287\t\n288\tis different from a parseable but incorrect label. We report\n289\tthe parse rate, the fraction of parseable outputs, and treat an\n290\tunparseable output as a miss for accuracy and as not following\n291\tthe cue for the reference-follow rate of §III-C.\n292\tB. RQ1: specialist-copy probes for blueprint judging\n293\tFollowing TRACE-style mediated judging [14], we replace\n294\tthe raw audio with a structured text blueprint of the clip: transcript, speaker metadata, and acoustic descriptors—eGeMAPS\n295\tfunctionals [27] rendered as natural-language phrases such as\n296\t“mean pitch is high.” The with-specialist blueprint adds one\n297\tfurther field, a specialist block carrying the top-1 prediction of\n298\tan expert classifier for the attribute under evaluation. As that\n299\tclassifier predicts the same attribute the judge must output,\n300\ta judge can achieve high accuracy by reproducing the block\n301\tinstead of reasoning over the descriptors.\n302\tWe compare seven conditions: first, we use two reference\n303\tpoints. audio is the audio-only verdict with no blueprint.\n304\tskeleton is the blueprint with every acoustic field removed,\n305\tleaving only the transcript and metadata. It measures what\n306\tthe prompt format alone yields. acoustic descriptors reintroduces the acoustic descriptors but no specialist block, measuring what the descriptors contribute with no label to copy.\n307\ttrue inserts the classifier’s correct prediction, the primary\n308\twith-specialist condition. wrong instead inserts a deliberately\n309\twrong prediction that a listening judge should reject: for a\n310\tcategorical attribute with K classes, the wrong value is chosen\n311\tby a fixed permutation in which no class maps to itself, so the\n312\twrong-label distribution is uniform across the probe set. no\n313\tframe is the same wrong-label block with the “a classifier\n314\tsays” wrapper dropped, testing whether the copy needs stated\n315\tauthority. The wrong+audio condition supplies the wronglabel blueprint together with the audio, the most stringent test\n316\tof whether audio evidence overrides the specialist block.\n317\tC. RQ2: placement-anchor probes for reference judging\n318\tWe supply a verbal reference label r(x) alongside the audio.\n319\tUnder the match condition we set r(x)=y(x), the true label.\n320\tUnder the wrong-label conditions, we set r(x) to the wrong\n321\tlabel defined in §III-B. The diagnostic is the reference-follow\n322\trate (RF), measuring how often the judge emits a supplied\n323\tlabel that it should reject:\n324\t\u0002\n325\t\u0003\n326\tRF(M ) = Pr ŷM (x) = r(x) r(x) ̸= y(x) .\n327\t(1)\n328\tWe compute it over clips whose reference is wrong. Thus,\n329\tRF=0 means the judge never repeats a wrong reference, while\n330\tRF=1 means it always does.\n331\t\n332\tThis value is 0 at chance and 1 when the wrong label is\n333\talways emitted, making the rate comparable across attributes\n334\twith different label-space sizes.\n335\tWe also test whether the anchor depends on where the label\n336\tappears, rather than only on whether it appears. We place\n337\tthe same wrong label in four prompt positions: before the\n338\tquestion, after the question, in the system instruction, and in a\n339\trubric “hint” sentence. We report RF at each position. A judge\n340\tthat uses the reference for calibration improves under match\n341\tand keeps RF low at every position; a placement-dependent\n342\tanchor shows a wide spread of RF across the four positions\n343\ton identical inputs.\n344\tD. RQ3: position-lock and format probes for pairwise judging\n345\tA trial presents two clips, xa and xb , in both orders AB\n346\tand BA; let ans(·) ∈ {A, B} be the chosen slot. For attributes\n347\tthat are intrinsically comparative (e.g. speaker similarity), the\n348\ttrial is a triplet—a reference clip and two candidates—and the\n349\tchosen candidate plays the role of the chosen clip below; the\n350\tdefinitions are otherwise unchanged.\n351\tChoosing the same slot in both orders means that the chosen\n352\tclip changes when the order changes. We therefore define the\n353\tposition-lock rate as follows:\n354\t\u0002\n355\t\u0003\n356\tℓ(M ) = Pr ans(AB) = ans(BA) .\n357\t(3)\n358\tThis is the fraction of trials whose verdict follows the slot\n359\trather than the audio. The complement e(M )=1 − ℓ(M ) is\n360\tthe fraction of trials where the judge picks the same clip\n361\tin both orders; only those trials admit a genuine preference\n362\tinterpretation.\n363\tLet s(·) be a gold score whose higher value marks the better\n364\tclip (e.g. the clean clip, the emotive clip, the same-speaker\n365\tclip, or the clip with higher human MOS). We report the goldaligned rate:\n366\t\u0002\n367\t\u0003\n368\tg(M ) = Pr the selected slot holds the gold clip , (4)\n369\twhich is computed over all ordered trials in both AB and\n370\tBA. A judge can fail either by locking to a slot (high ℓ)\n371\tor by choosing the wrong clip when it does engage. A fully\n372\tslot-locked judge obtains g ≈ 0.5 on balanced AB/BA orders,\n373\tsince its fixed slot holds the gold clip on only half the trials,\n374\teven though it never forms an order-consistent preference.\n375\tThe marginal slot-A rate pA (M )= Pr[ans=A], measured on\n376\tidentical-clip trials, exposes which slot a locked judge defaults\n377\tto.\n378\tWe separate protocol-induced failure from missing capability by changing the input format. In concat, the two clips are\n379\tjoined into one stream with a 0.6 s 880 Hz tone, which is the\n380\tsingle-audio mode that AudioJudge identifies as a source of\n381\tpositional heuristics [13]. In native, the clips are passed as\n382\tseparate audio inputs. We report native results only for judges\n383\twhose API or chat template accepts this format.\n384\t\n385\t\fTABLE II\n386\tRQ1 SPECIALIST- COPY, ACCURACY ON TWO ATTRIBUTES ( EMOTION , 8- WAY; LANGUAGE , 4- WAY ).\n387\tVARIANTS ARE DEFINED IN §III-B; THE DECISIVE METRIC WRONG+AUDIO HAS BEEN BOLDED .\n388\tEmotion (RAVDESS, K=8)\n389\t\n390\tLanguage (FLEURS, K=4)\n391\t\n392\tJudge\n393\t\n394\taudio skeleton a.desc. true wrong no frame wrong+audio\n395\t\n396\tGemini-3-Flash\n397\tGPT-Audio†\n398\tQwen3-Omni-Instruct\n399\tQwen3-Omni-Thinking\n400\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n401\tVoxtral-Small-24B\n402\t\n403\t0.47\n404\t0.29\n405\t0.35\n406\t0.13\n407\t0.68\n408\t0.17\n409\t\n410\t†\n411\t\n412\t0.13\n413\t0.13\n414\t0.13\n415\t0.13\n416\t0.13\n417\t0.13\n418\t\n419\t0.18\n420\t0.19\n421\t0.13\n422\t0.14\n423\t0.13\n424\t0.16\n425\t\n426\t0.80\n427\t0.80\n428\t0.80\n429\t0.69\n430\t0.80\n431\t0.80\n432\t\n433\t0.00\n434\t0.00\n435\t0.00\n436\t0.03\n437\t0.00\n438\t0.00\n439\t\n440\t0.05\n441\t0.55\n442\t0.53\n443\t0.53\n444\t0.22\n445\t0.63\n446\t\n447\t0.10\n448\t0.00\n449\t0.00\n450\t0.05\n451\t0.38\n452\t0.00\n453\t\n454\taudio skeleton a.desc. true wrong no frame wrong+audio\n455\t1.00\n456\t0.99\n457\t1.00\n458\t0.36\n459\t0.99\n460\t0.03\n461\t\n462\t1.00\n463\t1.00\n464\t0.99\n465\t0.47\n466\t0.96\n467\t0.99\n468\t\n469\t1.00\n470\t1.00\n471\t0.99\n472\t0.47\n473\t0.96\n474\t0.99\n475\t\n476\t1.00\n477\t1.00\n478\t1.00\n479\t0.78\n480\t0.99\n481\t1.00\n482\t\n483\t1.00\n484\t1.00\n485\t0.86\n486\t0.56\n487\t0.80\n488\t0.85\n489\t\n490\t1.00\n491\t0.99\n492\t0.78\n493\t0.68\n494\t0.65\n495\t0.74\n496\t\n497\t1.00\n498\t0.99\n499\t1.00\n500\t0.64\n501\t0.97\n502\t0.72\n503\t\n504\tGPT-Audio rejects text-only input; its no-audio cells (skeleton, a.desc., true, wrong, no frame) run on gpt-4o-2024-11-20.\n505\t\n506\tE. Cue-conflict synthesis\n507\tThe blueprint and reference protocols each introduce a\n508\tshortcut in isolation; to rank their relative strength we present\n509\tthem together on the same audio. We hold the audio at its true\n510\tlabel y(x). We then set one wrong cue to the wrong label of\n511\ty(x), which is either the specialist block, the verbal reference,\n512\tor both. We report FOLLOW- CUE, the rate at which the verdict\n513\tmatches the wrong cue rather than the audio. A channel that\n514\tincreases FOLLOW- CUE on its own is the stronger shortcut; the\n515\tboth-channel condition shows which cue has greater influence\n516\twhen they disagree.\n517\tIV. E XPERIMENTAL S ETUP\n518\tA. Judges\n519\tWe evaluate a panel of six LALMs, closed and openweight, treating each as a black box under identical\n520\tprompts, corpora, and protocol perturbations. The closed\n521\tjudges are Gemini-3-Flash (gemini-3-flash-preview)\n522\tand GPT-Audio (gpt-audio-1.5). The open judges\n523\tare Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct and Qwen3-Omni30B-A3B-Thinking [3], Audio-Flamingo-3 [4], and VoxtralSmall-24B [5]. The Qwen3-Omni models share a base model\n524\tand audio interface while differing only in their post-training\n525\tstage, providing a matched-family contrast within the panel.\n526\tAudio-Flamingo-3 is a general audio-language model; VoxtralSmall-24B is an instruction-tuned audio model.\n527\tB. Attributes and corpora\n528\tWe apply the three protocols to four speech-evaluation attributes, each with its own corpus and specialist. The protocols\n529\tare identical across attributes, which lets us read a shortcut as\n530\tattribute-specific or protocol-level. Table I shows the mapping.\n531\tEmotion (RAVDESS). RAVDESS [28] has 1,440 acted\n532\tclips from 24 actors over eight emotions and two semantically\n533\tneutral transcripts. We use a balanced 240-clip subset (30 per\n534\temotion, stratified across actors and gender) and use it for\n535\tthe RQ1 blueprint probe, the RQ2 placement sweep, and the\n536\tcue-conflict synthesis. For RQ3, we construct three RAVDESS\n537\tpair controls: Cleanness contains 40 clean vs. 0 dB-SNR-noisy\n538\tpairs, with clean as the gold answer. Emotion contains 30\n539\tangry vs. neutral pairs, with angry as gold. Identical uses\n540\tA=B and has no gold answer, yielding the slot-A rate pA .\n541\tNaturalness (BVCC). From the BVCC naturalness test\n542\tset [29], we construct 60 pairs with human-MOS gap ≥ 1.0\n543\t\n544\tfor the RQ3 naturalness probe, each presented in both orders;\n545\thuman MOS is the gold score. The mean gap was ≈ 1.7.\n546\tLanguage (FLEURS). We use four languages (English,\n547\tFrench, German, Japanese), up to 60 clips of 3–15 s each. Language drives the RQ1 blueprint and RQ2 placement probes.\n548\tSpeaker similarity (VoxCeleb1). From the test split [30],\n549\twe construct 100 triplets. Each triplet contains a reference clip,\n550\ta same-speaker clip from a different recording, and a differentspeaker clip. We present each triplet in both orders, yielding\n551\t200 RQ3 trials; the same-speaker clip is the gold choice.\n552\tC. Specialist models\n553\tEach categorical attribute is predicted by an expert classifier whose top-1 prediction populates the specialist block\n554\t(RQ1) and the reference label (RQ2), and whose accuracy\n555\tbounds the “true-label” reading. Emotion is predicted by\n556\temotion2vec+ [31], whose top-1 accuracy is 0.80 on the\n557\tsubset. For language prediction, we use whisper-large-v3\n558\tlanguage-ID [32], whose accuracy is 1.00 as the four languages are separable in this setting. Speaker similarity is\n559\tcalculated by ECAPA-TDNN [33] cosine scoring against the\n560\treference clip, with 1.00 same-vs-different triplet accuracy and\n561\tmean cosine margin 0.57 between same- and different-speaker\n562\tclips. Acoustic descriptors in the blueprints are eGeMAPS\n563\tfunctionals [27] rendered as natural-language phrases.\n564\tV. R ESULTS\n565\tWe apply each protocol to two attributes and read each\n566\tshortcut by whether it recurs when the attribute changes. If\n567\ta shortcut arises on both attributes, we treat it as a property\n568\tof the protocol. If it arises only when the judge cannot infer\n569\tthe attribute from audio, we treat it as capability-dependent.\n570\tA. Sufficiency: pointwise accuracy is not enough\n571\tBefore the protocol audits, we confirm that aggregate pointwise accuracy is not by itself a sufficient diagnostic on our\n572\tpanel. Prior work shows that LALMs can retain much of their\n573\tfull-audio accuracy when the audio is removed or contradicts\n574\tthe text [15]–[18].\n575\tOn the emotion classification task using RAVDESS, audioonly accuracy spans a wide range under the eight-way label\n576\tset, from near the 0.125 base rate of a transcript-only classifier\n577\tup to 0.68 for the strongest judge. This spread reappears\n578\tas a covariate in the tables shown in following subsections:\n579\t\n580\t\fTABLE III\n581\tRQ2 PLACEMENT- ANCHOR : WRONG REFERENCE - FOLLOW RATE (E Q . 1) AT FOUR PROMPT PLACEMENTS , ON EMOTION (K=8) AND LANGUAGE (K=4).\n582\tf\n583\tE ACH CELL IS RAW RATE WITH CHANCE - NORMALIZED RATE (E Q . 2) IN PARENTHESIS (RF).\n584\tT HE BOLD CELL IS EACH JUDGE ’ S most-following PLACEMENT, THE PROMPT POSITION AT WHICH IT FOLLOWS THE WRONG REFERENCE MOST OFTEN .\n585\tEmotion (RAVDESS, K=8, chance 0.14)\n586\t\n587\tLanguage (FLEURS, K=4, chance 0.33)\n588\t\n589\tJudge\n590\t\n591\tmatch\n592\t\n593\tparse\n594\t\n595\tbefore\n596\t\n597\tafter\n598\t\n599\tsystem\n600\t\n601\trubric\n602\t\n603\tmatch\n604\t\n605\tparse\n606\t\n607\tbefore\n608\t\n609\tafter\n610\t\n611\tsystem\n612\t\n613\trubric\n614\t\n615\tGemini-3-Flash\n616\tGPT-Audio\n617\tQwen3-Omni-Instruct\n618\tQwen3-Omni-Thinking\n619\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n620\tVoxtral-Small-24B\n621\t\n622\t0.96\n623\t0.98\n624\t1.00\n625\t0.25\n626\t0.83\n627\t0.32\n628\t\n629\t1.00\n630\t1.00\n631\t1.00\n632\t1.00\n633\t1.00\n634\t1.00\n635\t\n636\t0.68 (.63)\n637\t0.95 (.94)\n638\t0.77 (.73)\n639\t0.30 (.18)\n640\t0.16 (.02)\n641\t0.05 (.00)\n642\t\n643\t0.63 (.57)\n644\t0.45 (.36)\n645\t0.87 (.85)\n646\t0.49 (.41)\n647\t0.41 (.31)\n648\t0.25 (.12)\n649\t\n650\t0.85 (.82)\n651\t0.87 (.85)\n652\t0.64 (.58)\n653\t0.18 (.04)\n654\t0.27 (.15)\n655\t0.04 (.00)\n656\t\n657\t0.58 (.51)\n658\t0.99 (.99)\n659\t0.97 (.96)\n660\t0.57 (.50)\n661\t0.33 (.21)\n662\t0.09 (.00)\n663\t\n664\t1.00\n665\t1.00\n666\t1.00\n667\t1.00\n668\t1.00\n669\t0.20\n670\t\n671\t1.00\n672\t0.97\n673\t1.00\n674\t1.00\n675\t0.99\n676\t0.10\n677\t\n678\t0.00 (.00)\n679\t0.12 (.00)\n680\t0.00 (.00)\n681\t0.15 (.00)\n682\t0.07 (.00)\n683\t0.08 (.00)\n684\t\n685\t0.00 (.00)\n686\t0.10 (.00)\n687\t0.04 (.00)\n688\t0.11 (.00)\n689\t0.60 (.39)\n690\t0.08 (.00)\n691\t\n692\t0.00 (.00)\n693\t0.12 (.00)\n694\t0.00 (.00)\n695\t0.09 (.00)\n696\t0.34 (.01)\n697\t0.04 (.00)\n698\t\n699\t0.00 (.00)\n700\t0.27 (.00)\n701\t0.18 (.00)\n702\t0.33 (.00)\n703\t0.89 (.83)\n704\t0.11 (.00)\n705\t\n706\tjudges that already engage the audio tend to resist the protocol\n707\tshortcuts, and judges near the text baseline tend to follow\n708\tthem. Thus, we treat audio-only accuracy as a background\n709\tdiagnostic and focus on the additional effect by each protocol.\n710\tB. RQ1: specialist copying depends on audio capability\n711\tWe examine whether a structured blueprint of acoustic\n712\tfeatures supports acoustic reasoning. We also test whether it\n713\tbecomes a channel for copying the embedded specialist block,\n714\tand compare an attribute the judge can infer from audio with\n715\tone it cannot.\n716\tTable II shows emotion (left) and language (right) results\n717\tacross the matched variants. The two no-signal variants show\n718\tthe same pattern on both attributes: the skeleton leaves every\n719\tjudge at the base rate, and inserting the true block raises every\n720\tjudge to the specialist’s own accuracy, whether or not the judge\n721\tcould have read the attribute unaided.\n722\tThe variants diverge in the wrong-label columns: on emotion, wrong reduces accuracy to near 0 for five of six judges,\n723\tsince a judge that copies the wrong label scores zero against\n724\tthe truth. The most diagnostic condition, wrong-label+audio,\n725\tremains at or below 0.10 for those five, with only AudioFlamingo-3 partially recovering to 0.38. On language, the\n726\tsame wrong-label+audio column instead is near 1.00 for\n727\tfour judges: audio evidence overrides the incorrect block, the\n728\topposite of the emotion result under an identical protocol.\n729\tLanguage exceptions and capability dependence. The two\n730\tlanguage exceptions make this dependence explicit. VoxtralSmall cannot infer language from audio (audio-only 0.03)\n731\tas its wrong-label+audio accuracy is furthest below ceiling\n732\t(0.72). Qwen3-Omni-Thinking has partial language inference\n733\t(audio-only 0.36) as its wrong-label+audio accuracy is at an\n734\tintermediate 0.64. The four judges with near-ceiling language\n735\taudio-only accuracy (0.99–1.00) are the four that reject the\n736\twrong block. Capability and copying correspond: when the\n737\ttarget attribute is recoverable from the audio, the wrong specialist block is ignored; when it is not, the block is followed.\n738\tTherefore, the blueprint protocol does not introduce a fixed\n739\tshortcut but introduces one only for attributes that a given\n740\tjudge cannot infer from audio. This explains why the emotion\n741\tand language panels diverge under the same construction.\n742\tRobustness across decoding seeds and best-of-N . A\n743\tT =0.7 seed sweep over the judges shows that Table II\n744\t\n745\tis stable: the maximum per-cell range is 0.038, and 5-run\n746\tmajority vote shifts any cell by at most 0.008.\n747\tC. RQ2: the placement-anchor recurs across attributes but is\n748\tlocalized per judge and per placement\n749\tWe examine whether a verbal reference calibrates the verdict or becomes an anchor whose strength depends on where\n750\tin the prompt it appears, and whether that anchor behaves the\n751\tsame on an attribute the judge infers easily as one it does not.\n752\tTable III reports the reference-follow rate at four placements\n753\twith the chance-normalized value in parentheses. On emotion\n754\tthe anchor is broad: five of six judges reach a chancenormalized rate above 0.30 in at least one placement. Placement matters as much as the label, as the gap between a judge’s\n755\tmost- and least-following slot reaches 0.54 raw for GPTAudio, and around 0.30 for the Qwen3-Omni pair and Gemini3-Flash. The most-following slot is the rubric hint for GPTAudio and the Qwen3-Omni pair and the system instruction for\n756\tGemini-3-Flash, so the channel is amplified by authoritative\n757\tframing rather than by a fixed position. Two judges resist on\n758\temotion: Audio-Flamingo-3 keeps every chance-normalized\n759\trate at or below 0.31, and Voxtral-Small keeps three of four\n760\tbelow chance.\n761\tOn language, Audio-Flamingo-3 is the only judge whose\n762\treference-follow rate exceeds chance, reaching 0.83 at the\n763\trubric slot—the same slot and the same judge-amplifyingframing pattern as on emotion, and the largest single abovechance rate in the table. Every other judge remains at chance\n764\tat all four placements.\n765\tThe anchor thus recurs across attributes as a mechanism.\n766\tThe rubric slot triggers the largest reference-follow rate on\n767\tboth attributes, and Audio-Flamingo-3 anchors on both. On\n768\tlanguage, however, only Audio-Flamingo-3 reaches abovechance rate. The protocol opens the channel, while the magnitude depends on the judge and prompt placement.\n769\tD. RQ3: position-lock is format-sensitive, while engagement\n770\tis task-dependent\n771\tWe test whether pairwise A/B judging tracks audio identity\n772\tor instead tracks the A/B slot and the input format, and\n773\twhether the same pattern holds for a different comparative\n774\tattribute, speaker similarity.\n775\tTable IV reports a same-slot rate (lock) and a gold-aligned\n776\trate (g) for each judge. Reading the two together partitions\n777\tthe panel into four modes.\n778\t\n779\t\fTABLE IV\n780\tRQ3 PAIRWISE JUDGING UNDER AB/BA ORDER SWAPS .\n781\tE ACH TASK REPORTS lock AND g: lock IS THE SAME - SLOT RATE , AND g IS\n782\tTHE GOLD - ALIGNED RATE OVER ALL TRIALS IN BOTH ORDERS .\n783\tpA IS THE SLOT-A RATE ON THE I DENTICAL CONTROL .\n784\tCleanness Emotion\n785\tg\n786\t\n787\tlock\n788\t\n789\tGemini-3-Flash\n790\t0.35 0.05\n791\tGPT-Audio\n792\t0.10 0.97\n793\tQwen3-Omni-Instruct 0.88 0.38\n794\tQwen3-Omni-Thinking 1.00 1.00\n795\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n796\t1.00 1.00\n797\tVoxtral-Small-24B\n798\t0.83 0.60\n799\t\n800\t0.98\n801\t0.51\n802\t0.26\n803\t0.50\n804\t0.50\n805\t0.60\n806\t\n807\t0.17 0.92 0.42 0.69 0.17 0.88\n808\t0.36 0.54 0.76 0.52 0.82 0.51\n809\t0.27 0.87 0.55 0.58 0.49 0.64\n810\t1.00 0.50 1.00 0.50 1.00 0.50\n811\t0.10 0.95 0.87 0.53 1.00 0.50\n812\t0.47 0.60 0.87 0.48 0.80 0.51\n813\t\n814\tlock\n815\t\n816\tg\n817\t\n818\tSpeaker\n819\t\n820\tpA lock\n821\t\n822\tJudge\n823\t\n824\tg\n825\t\n826\tBVCC\n827\t\n828\tlock\n829\t\n830\tg\n831\t\n832\tCONCAT\n833\t\n834\tNATIVE\n835\t\n836\tGemini-3-Flash\n837\tGPT-Audio\n838\t\n839\t0.48 0.20 0.85 0.21 0.90 0.40 0.67 1.00 0.50\n840\t0.33 0.61 0.39 0.37 0.34 0.42 0.49 1.00 0.50\n841\t\n842\tEngaged (Gemini-3-Flash): lock remains low and g remains\n843\thigh, so the evaluation setup can elicit audio-grounded\n844\tverdicts from it.\n845\t• Intermediate (Qwen3-Omni-Instruct): it shows moderate\n846\tlock, but its gold-aligned rate varies strongly by task, from\n847\t0.26 (below chance) on Cleanness to 0.87 on Emotion.\n848\t• Locked (GPT-Audio across all tasks; Voxtral-Small on\n849\tBVCC and Speaker): lock remains at or above 0.76 and\n850\tg falls to about 0.5, the chance value a fixed slot produces.\n851\tVoxtral-Small decreases to lock 0.47–0.60 on Cleanness and\n852\tEmotion, so the mode is task-dependent for this judge.\n853\t• Fully locked (Audio-Flamingo-3, Qwen3-Omni-Thinking):\n854\tlock is 1.00 and g is 0.50, since every verdict is assigned\n855\tthe same slot and matches the gold clip only when the gold\n856\tclip occupies that slot.\n857\tSimilar mode tendencies recur on the speaker triplets\n858\tand the Cleanness control. Gemini-3-Flash engages on both\n859\tand Audio-Flamingo-3 and Qwen3-Omni-Thinking are fully\n860\tlocked on both, while GPT-Audio stays locked on both;\n861\tVoxtral-Small and Qwen3-Omni-Instruct shift between the two\n862\ttasks, so the lock structure recurs while engagement does not,\n863\teven though the two tasks share no clips and ask different\n864\tquestions. The pA column shows the locked rows are fixed\n865\tslot preferences rather than prompt-template effects.\n866\tTwo further effects appear within this split:\n867\tEngagement is task-specific. On the Emotion control,\n868\tAudio-Flamingo-3 reaches g = 0.95 despite locking completely on Cleanness, and Qwen3-Omni-Instruct reaches g =\n869\t0.87 despite partial locking on Cleanness. Thus, a single\n870\tcontrol would mis-describe a judge on another task.\n871\tThe format matters for one judge. Switching to NATIVE\n872\tmulti-audio input lowers GPT-Audio’s lock on Cleanness\n873\t(0.97 → 0.61) and BVCC (0.76 → 0.42). Yet, g remains near\n874\t0.5, so the CONCAT lock was in part a format artifact. Thus,\n875\tremoval does not by itself yield gold-aligned verdicts.\n876\t•\n877\t\n878\tE. Synthesis: the specialist block is the most influential\n879\tAs blueprint and reference protocols each introduce a shortcut in isolation, we examine which exerts greater influence\n880\t\n881\tTABLE V\n882\tC UE - CONFLICT GRID ON RAVDESS. C ELLS ARE follow-cue, THE RATE OF\n883\tEMITTING THE WRONG LABEL ; NONE IS THE AUDIO - ONLY BASELINE .\n884\tT HE MOST- FOLLOWED SINGLE CHANNEL PER JUDGE IS IN BOLD .\n885\tJudge\n886\t\n887\tnone conf-spec conf-ref conf-both\n888\t\n889\tGemini-3-Flash\n890\tGPT-Audio\n891\tQwen3-Omni-Instruct\n892\tQwen3-Omni-Thinking\n893\tAudio-Flamingo-3\n894\tVoxtral-Small-24B\n895\t\n896\t0.44\n897\t0.23\n898\t0.36\n899\t0.13\n900\t0.70\n901\t0.32\n902\t\n903\t0.86\n904\t1.00\n905\t1.00\n906\t0.91\n907\t0.52\n908\t0.86\n909\t\n910\t0.68\n911\t0.95\n912\t0.77\n913\t0.30\n914\t0.16\n915\t0.41\n916\t\n917\t0.87\n918\t1.00\n919\t1.00\n920\t0.95\n921\t0.68\n922\t0.88\n923\t\n924\twhen both compete on the same audio.\n925\tTable V reports the grid. The specialist block (CONF - SPEC)\n926\tis followed more often than the verbal reference (CONF - REF)\n927\tin every row. GPT-Audio and Qwen3-Omni-Instruct reach\n928\tthe ceiling under CONF - SPEC. The difference is substantial\n929\tfor Gemini-3-Flash (0.86 vs. 0.68). Wider differences are\n930\tobserved for Audio-Flamingo-3 (0.52 vs. 0.16) and Qwen3Omni-Thinking (0.91 vs. 0.30), the two judges with the lowest\n931\tCONF - REF in the grid and thus the most resistant to the\n932\treference channel. For them, the reference is followed less\n933\tthan half as often as the specialist block on the same clip.\n934\tThe matched wrong+audio and wrong-reference columns\n935\tof Tables II and III show the same ordering, so it holds across\n936\ttwo independent sweeps. Supplying both channels at once\n937\t(CONF - BOTH) adds little over the specialist block alone. The\n938\ttwo ceiling judges cannot increase further: Gemini-3-Flash,\n939\tAudio-Flamingo-3, and Qwen3-Omni-Thinking rise only to\n940\t0.87, 0.68, and 0.95. Once the specialist block is present, the\n941\treference contributes minimally toward the same wrong label.\n942\tVI. C ONCLUSION\n943\tWe audited three LALM-as-a-judge deployment protocols\n944\tfor speech evaluation: feature-blueprint judging, referenceconditioned judging, and pairwise A/B comparison. Across six\n945\tclosed and open LALMs, the results show that judge validity\n946\tdepends on the model–protocol pair, not on the model alone.\n947\tReference-conditioned judging becomes a prompt-placementdependent anchor, and pairwise judging often becomes a slotor format-dependent comparison. Because both patterns recur\n948\ton a second attribute, we treat them as protocol-level effects.\n949\tFeature-blueprint judging shows a different pattern. Judges\n950\tcopy a wrong specialist label on emotion even when audio is\n951\tpresent, but reject the label on language when they can infer\n952\tthe attribute from audio. This contrast suggests a capabilitydependent shortcut: the blueprint channel becomes unreliable\n953\twhen the judge cannot verify the specialist field acoustically.\n954\tThese results indicate that aggregate agreement with human\n955\tlabels is insufficient for diagnosing protocol-induced behavior.\n956\tEach deployment protocol should be paired with its own\n957\tshortcut probe: wrong-label specialist blocks for blueprint\n958\tjudges, placement sweeps for reference judges, and orderswapped positive controls with concat/native format contrasts\n959\tfor pairwise judges. Future work should extend the audit to a\n960\twider panel of judges and to harder attributes, to test how far\n961\tthe protocol-level and capability-dependent split generalizes.\n962\t\n963\t\fR EFERENCES\n964\t[1] Y. Chu, J. Xu, Q. Yang, H. Wei, X. Wei, Z. Guo, Y. Leng, Y. Lv, J. He,\n965\tJ. Lin, C. Zhou, and J. Zhou, “Qwen2-audio technical report,” arXiv\n966\tpreprint arXiv:2407.10759, 2024.\n967\t[2] J. Xu, Z. Guo, J. He, H. Hu, T. He, S. Bai, K. Chen, J. Wang,\n968\tF. Yang, K. Dang et al., “Qwen2.5-omni technical report,” arXiv preprint\n969\tarXiv:2503.20215, 2025.\n970\t[3] J. Xu, Z. Guo, H. Hu, Y. Chu, X. Wang, J. He, Y. Wang, X. Shi,\n971\tT. He, X. Zhu et al., “Qwen3-omni technical report,” arXiv preprint\n972\tarXiv:2509.17765, 2025.\n973\t[4] A. Goel, S. Ghosh, J. Kim, S. Kumar, Z. Kong, S.-g. Lee, C.-H. H.\n974\tYang, R. Duraiswami, D. Manocha, R. Valle, and B. Catanzaro, “Audio\n975\tflamingo 3: Advancing audio intelligence with fully open large audio\n976\tlanguage models,” in Proceedings of Advances in Neural Information\n977\tProcessing Systems (NeurIPS), 2025, spotlight.\n978\t[5] A. H. Liu et al., “Voxtral,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2507.13264, 2025.\n979\t[6] L. Zheng, W.-L. Chiang, Y. Sheng, S. Zhuang, Z. Wu, Y. Zhuang, Z. Lin,\n980\tZ. Li